documents.content: RESTRICTED - INTERNAL USE ONLY Cybersecurity Incident Response Playbook Version 3.2 - November 2025 Table of Contents: 1. Introduction and Scope 2. Incident Classification Matrix 3. Response Team Structure 4. Phase 1: Detection and Analysis 5. Phase 2: Containment and Eradication 6. Phase 3: Recovery and Post-Incident 7. Communication Protocols 8. Appendices and References 1. Introduction and Scope This playbook provides standardized procedures for responding to cybersecurity incidents within our organization. It establishes clear roles, responsibilities, and escalation paths to ensure rapid and effective incident response. 1.1 Incident Definition A cybersecurity incident is defined as any event that compromises or threatens to compromise the confidentiality, integrity, or availability of information systems or data. 1.2 Scope of Coverage  Malware infections and advanced persistent threats  Unauthorized access attempts and successful breaches  Data theft or exfiltration incidents  Denial of service attacks  Insider threat activities  Third-party vendor security incidents 2. Incident Classification Matrix 2.1 Severity Levels CRITICAL (P1) - Immediate Response Required:  Active data exfiltration in progress  Complete system compromise of critical infrastructure  Ransomware encryption of production systems  Nation-state actor attribution with ongoing activity HIGH (P2) - Response Within 2 Hours:  Confirmed malware on production systems  Successful lateral movement detected  Privilege escalation attempts  Suspicious administrative account activity MEDIUM (P3) - Response Within 8 Hours:  Failed authentication attempts from external sources  Suspicious network traffic patterns  Policy violations by authorized users  Vulnerability exploitation attempts 3. Incident Response Team Structure 3.1 Core Team Members  Incident Commander - Overall response coordination  Security Analyst - Technical investigation and analysis  Systems Administrator - Infrastructure containment and recovery  Communications Lead - Internal and external notifications  Legal Counsel - Regulatory compliance and legal implications  Executive Sponsor - Senior leadership representation 3.2 Contact Information  Emergency Hotline: +1-555-SECURITY (24/7)  Incident Commander: incident-commander@company.com  Security Operations Center: soc@company.com  Executive Escalation: ciso@company.com 4. Phase 1: Detection and Analysis 4.1 Initial Triage Checklist  Verify the incident report and gather initial details  Classify the incident severity using the matrix above  Activate appropriate response team members  Establish incident tracking and documentation  Begin preliminary technical analysis  Preserve evidence and maintain chain of custody 4.2 Evidence Collection Procedures All evidence collection must follow forensically sound practices:  Create bit-for-bit disk images using validated tools  Capture volatile memory contents before system shutdown  Document all actions taken with timestamps  Maintain proper chain of custody documentation  Store evidence in secure, access-controlled environment 5. Phase 2: Containment and Eradication 5.1 Short-term Containment  Isolate affected systems from the network  Disable compromised user accounts  Block malicious IP addresses and domains  Update firewall rules and IPS signatures  Implement temporary access controls 5.2 Long-term Containment and Eradication  Remove malware and malicious artifacts  Patch vulnerabilities that enabled the incident  Rebuild compromised systems from known-good sources  Update security controls and monitoring  Implement additional protective measures 6. Phase 3: Recovery and Post-Incident 6.1 System Recovery Procedures 

temporary access controls 5.2 Long-term Containment and Eradication  Remove malware and malicious artifacts  Patch vulnerabilities that enabled the incident  Rebuild compromised systems from known-good sources  Update security controls and monitoring  Implement additional protective measures 6. Phase 3: Recovery and Post-Incident 6.1 System Recovery Procedures  Restore systems and data from clean backups  Validate system integrity and functionality  Implement enhanced monitoring for affected systems  Gradually restore normal operations  Document all recovery actions taken 6.2 Post-Incident Activities  Conduct lessons learned session within 48 hours  Update incident response procedures based on findings  Complete regulatory notification requirements  Provide final incident report to stakeholders  Schedule follow-up security assessments 7. Communication Protocols 7.1 Internal Notifications Critical incidents (P1) require immediate notification to:  Chief Information Security Officer (CISO)  Chief Technology Officer (CTO)  Chief Executive Officer (CEO)  Legal and Compliance teams  Human Resources (if insider threat suspected)  Public Relations (if media exposure likely) 7.2 External Notifications  Law enforcement (if criminal activity suspected)  Regulatory bodies (within required timeframes)  Cyber threat intelligence sharing organizations  Affected customers and business partners  Cyber insurance providers  External legal counsel (if required) 8. Appendices and References Appendix A: Emergency Contact List [Contact information would be listed here with current phone numbers, email addresses, and escalation procedures] Appendix B: Technical Tools and Resources  SIEM Platform: Splunk Enterprise Security  Endpoint Detection: CrowdStrike Falcon  Network Analysis: Wireshark, tcpdump  Forensic Imaging: EnCase, FTK Imager  Malware Analysis: IDA Pro, Ghidra  Threat Intelligence: MISP, OpenCTI Appendix C: Regulatory Requirements This playbook addresses requirements from:  NIST Cybersecurity Framework  ISO 27035 Incident Management  GDPR Article 33 Breach Notification  SOX Section 404 Internal Controls  PCI DSS Requirement 12.10  State and federal breach notification laws Document Classification: RESTRICTED Last Updated: November 11, 2025 Next Review Date: February 11, 2026

CLASSIFIED - FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY Advanced Persistent Threat Analysis - APT-2025-001 Executive Summary: A sophisticated threat actor, designated APT-2025-001, has been identified targeting critical infrastructure across multiple sectors. The group exhibits advanced capabilities including zero-day exploits, custom malware, and sophisticated social engineering techniques. Key Findings:  Initial access via spear-phishing campaigns  Lateral movement using legitimate administrative tools  Data exfiltration over encrypted channels  Persistence through registry modifications Affected Sectors:  Energy and utilities - 45% of incidents  Financial services - 30% of incidents  Government agencies - 15% of incidents  Healthcare systems - 10% of incidents Technical Analysis: The threat actor employs a multi-stage malware framework consisting of: Stage 1 - Initial Dropper: MD5: 3a4b5c6d7e8f9a0b1c2d3e4f5a6b7c8d SHA256: 1234567890abcdef1234567890abcdef12345678 File size: 2.3MB Stage 2 - Persistence Module: Registry key: HKLM\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run Service installation: Windows Security Update Service Stage 3 - Command and Control: C2 servers: 192.168.45.123, 10.0.0.245 Communication protocol: HTTPS over port 443 Beacon interval: 30-120 minutes (randomized) Recommendations and Mitigation:  Deploy updated IOCs to all security tools  Enhance email security filtering  Implement additional network monitoring  Conduct threat hunting activities Classification: CONFIDENTIAL Report Date: November 11, 2025

CONFIDENTIAL - PACIFIC OPERATIONS INTELLIGENCE SITREP Classification: SECRET//NOFORN Report Period: Q4 2025 Distribution: Pacific Command, Allied Intelligence Partners Prepared by: Regional Threat Analysis Center EXECUTIVE SUMMARY ================ The Pacific theater has experienced a significant escalation in state-sponsored cyber activities during Q4 2025. Intelligence indicates coordinated campaigns targeting critical infrastructure across Australia, Japan, South Korea, and allied military installations throughout the region. Key developments include the emergence of a sophisticated threat actor designated APT-TSUNAMI, attributed with high confidence to a Pacific Rim nation-state. This group has demonstrated advanced capabilities including zero-day exploitation, custom firmware implants, and quantum-resistant encryption techniques. CURRENT THREAT LANDSCAPE ======================== Primary Threat Actors: APT-TSUNAMI (New Designation - October 2025) • Attribution: High confidence - Pacific Rim state actor • Capabilities: Advanced persistent access, quantum-resistant crypto • Targets: Military communications, submarine detection systems • Recent Activity: Infiltration of allied naval command systems APT-DRAGON-PEARL (Established Actor) • Attribution: Medium confidence - Eastern regional power • Capabilities: Supply chain compromise, hardware implants • Targets: Semiconductor facilities, 5G infrastructure • Recent Activity: Targeting TSMC and Samsung manufacturing PACIFIC-PHANTOM (Emerging Group) • Attribution: Low confidence - Possible proxy organization • Capabilities: Social engineering, deepfake technology • Targets: Diplomatic communications, trade negotiations • Recent Activity: Targeting ASEAN summit preparations REGIONAL INCIDENTS OF NOTE ========================== October 15, 2025 - Australia Government Classification: PROTECTED • Cyber intrusion detected at Pine Gap facility • Malware designed to exfiltrate satellite telemetry data • Attribution: APT-TSUNAMI with medium confidence • Mitigation: Network isolation and system hardening completed October 22, 2025 - Japan Government Classification: 秘 (Confidential) • Maritime Self-Defense Force communications compromised • Custom firmware implant discovered in radio equipment • Potential impact on submarine detection capabilities • Investigation ongoing with US Cyber Command support November 1, 2025 - South Korea Government Classification: 비밀 (Secret) • Advanced malware targeting K-Defense contractor networks • Focus on next-generation fighter aircraft specifications • Supply chain vector through compromised development tools • Joint response with US Forces Korea initiated November 8, 2025 - Philippines Government Classification: CONFIDENTIAL • Distributed denial of service attacks on port facilities • Coordinated with territorial disputes in South China Sea • Economic impact estimated at $15M in shipping delays • Attribution assessment ongoing TECHNICAL ANALYSIS ================== Malware Family: TSUNAMI-WAVE • First observed: September 2025 • Infection vector: Spear-phishing with weaponized documents • Persistence: UEFI bootkit installation • Communication: Encrypted channels using quantum-resistant algorithms • Payload: Data exfiltration and remote access capability Network Infrastructure: • Command servers hosted on compromised cloud providers • DNS tunneling through legitimate services • Cryptocurrency-based payment infrastructure • Use of Tor and I2P for anonymization Zero-Day Exploits: • CVE-2025-PENDING-001: Network equipment firmware vulnerability • CVE-2025-PENDING-002: Satellite communication protocol weakness • CVE-2025-PENDING-003: Military radio encryption bypass INTELLIGENCE GAPS AND REQUIREMENTS ================================== Critical Intelligence Gaps: 1. APT-TSUNAMI command structure and decision-making process 2. Full scope of compromised military communication systems 3. Quantum cryptographic capabilities and implementation timeline 4. Supply chain infiltration extent across defense contractors Priority Collection Requirements: • Human intelligence on threat actor organization • Technical intelligence on quantum-resistant malware variants • Signals intelligence on encrypted command

structure and decision-making process 2. Full scope of compromised military communication systems 3. Quantum cryptographic capabilities and implementation timeline 4. Supply chain infiltration extent across defense contractors Priority Collection Requirements: • Human intelligence on threat actor organization • Technical intelligence on quantum-resistant malware variants • Signals intelligence on encrypted command communications • Geospatial intelligence on physical infrastructure locations OPERATIONAL IMPACT ASSESSMENT ============================= Military Readiness Impact: MODERATE • Communication security compromised in multiple theaters • Need for enhanced COMSEC procedures and equipment refresh • Potential operational security risks for sensitive missions Economic Impact: SIGNIFICANT • Semiconductor supply chain vulnerabilities exposed • Manufacturing delays affecting defense procurement • Estimated $2.8B in economic damages across region Strategic Impact: HIGH • Shift in regional cyber balance of power • Need for enhanced allied cooperation and intelligence sharing • Potential for escalation to kinetic conflict RECOMMENDATIONS AND MITIGATION ============================== Immediate Actions (0-30 days): 1. Deploy updated signatures for TSUNAMI-WAVE malware family 2. Implement enhanced monitoring for quantum cryptography indicators 3. Conduct emergency security assessment of all military communications 4. Establish secure communication channels with regional allies Medium-term Actions (30-90 days): 1. Accelerate quantum-resistant cryptography deployment timeline 2. Conduct comprehensive supply chain security reviews 3. Implement deception technology to detect advanced threats 4. Enhance information sharing with Five Eyes partners Long-term Strategic Actions (90+ days): 1. Develop Pacific-specific cyber deterrence strategy 2. Establish regional cyber defense cooperation framework 3. Create joint threat hunting and incident response capabilities 4. Invest in next-generation defensive technologies CLASSIFICATION GUIDANCE ====================== This document contains information that could reveal intelligence sources and methods if disclosed to unauthorized persons. Distribution is restricted to personnel with appropriate security clearances and operational need-to-know. Declassification: 25 years from date of publication Review Authority: Pacific Command Intelligence Directorate POC: [REDACTED] - Regional Threat Analysis Center Next Assessment: February 15, 2026 Confidence Level: HIGH (based on multiple independent sources)

AI-Enhanced Social Engineering: Deepfake technology integration into spear-phishing campaigns has increased success rates by an estimated 340%. Voice cloning attacks against C-suite executives reported across multiple Fortune 500 companies. Supply Chain Firmware Implants: Hardware-level compromises detected in networking equipment from three major vendors. Implants designed for long-term persistence and covert data exfiltration. THREAT ACTIVITY SUMMARY - EUROPEAN THEATER Classification: CONFIDENTIAL//EU EYES ONLY Report Period: Q4 2025 Prepared for: European Cybersecurity Agency Distribution: EU Member State CERTs, NATO Cyber Centre EXECUTIVE OVERVIEW ================== The European cybersecurity landscape in Q4 2025 has been marked by unprecedented levels of sophisticated threat activity. State-sponsored actors have intensified operations targeting critical energy infrastructure, with particular focus on renewable energy grid management systems and cross-border power interconnections. The period saw 156 confirmed advanced persistent threat incidents across EU member states, representing a 41% increase from Q3 2025. Notable trends include the weaponization of artificial intelligence for social engineering, supply chain compromises affecting multiple countries simultaneously, and the emergence of quantum-resistant attack methodologies. INCIDENT RESPONSE TIMELINE - OPERATION SHADOWNET Timeline: September 15 - October 30, 2025 Incident Classification: Level 3 (Critical) Lead Analyst: Sarah Johnson Incident Commander: John Smith PHASE 1: DETECTION & INITIAL RESPONSE ===================================== September 15, 2025 - 14:32 UTC • SIEM alert triggered: Unusual PowerShell execution on DC01 • Endpoint detection: Suspicious process injection detected • Initial triage initiated by SOC analyst Mike Chen September 15, 2025 - 15:45 UTC • Incident escalated to Level 2 (Medium) • Network isolation implemented for affected workstation • Memory dump and disk imaging initiated • Incident response team activated September 15, 2025 - 18:20 UTC • Lateral movement detected across multiple systems • Incident escalated to Level 3 (Critical) • CISO Robert Taylor notified • External IR firm CyberResponse Inc. engaged PHASE 2: CONTAINMENT & ANALYSIS =============================== September 16, 2025 - 08:00 UTC • Network segmentation implemented • 47 potentially compromised systems identified • Command and control communications blocked • Forensic analysis reveals custom backdoor September 17, 2025 - 12:30 UTC • Threat actor attribution: APT-GLACIER (high confidence) • Attack vector confirmed: Spear-phishing with weaponized PDF • Persistence mechanism: Registry modification and scheduled task • Data exfiltration confirmed: 2.3 TB over 10-day period September 18, 2025 - 09:15 UTC • Complete network containment achieved • All affected systems isolated and preserved for forensics • Clean backup systems prepared for recovery • Legal counsel Amanda Davis briefed on breach scope PHASE 3: ERADICATION & RECOVERY =============================== September 22, 2025 - 14:00 UTC • Malware eradication completed on all systems • Security patches applied to close attack vectors • New security monitoring rules deployed • Enhanced email filtering implemented September 25, 2025 - 10:30 UTC • System recovery initiated from clean backups • Additional security hardening applied • Multi-factor authentication deployed organization-wide • Network architecture redesigned with zero-trust principles October 1, 2025 - 16:45 UTC • Full operational capability restored • Enhanced monitoring showing no signs of re-infection • User awareness training campaign launched • Incident response procedures updated PHASE 4: POST-INCIDENT ACTIVITIES ================================= October 5, 2025 - 11:00 UTC • Comprehensive lessons learned session conducted • Post-incident report draft completed • Regulatory notifications submitted (required within 72 hours) • Customer and partner communications sent October 15, 2025 - 14:20 UTC • External penetration test initiated to validate security improvements • Threat hunting exercises conducted • Security awareness training completion: 94% of staff • Insurance claim filed for $2.1M in recovery costs October 30, 2025 - 09:00 UTC • Final incident report published • Security improvements validated through red team exercise • Incident officially closed • Quarterly security review scheduled KEY PERFORMANCE METRICS ======================= Time to Detection: 2 hours 13 minutes Time to Containment: 18 hours 8 minutes Time to Eradication: 7 days Time to Recovery: 16 days Total Incident Duration: 45 days False Positive Rate: 3.2% Evidence Preservation: 100% Regulatory Compliance: Met all deadlines Customer Impact: Minimal (< 2 hours downtime) LESSONS LEARNED =============== Strengths: + Rapid detection through SIEM correlation rules + Effective team coordination and communication + Comprehensive evidence collection and preservation + Successful

days Total Incident Duration: 45 days False Positive Rate: 3.2% Evidence Preservation: 100% Regulatory Compliance: Met all deadlines Customer Impact: Minimal (< 2 hours downtime) LESSONS LEARNED =============== Strengths: + Rapid detection through SIEM correlation rules + Effective team coordination and communication + Comprehensive evidence collection and preservation + Successful containment preventing further damage Areas for Improvement: - Initial triage could have been faster with better playbooks - Network segmentation should be proactive, not reactive - User awareness training needs more frequent updates - Backup validation procedures need strengthening RECOMMENDATIONS =============== 1. Implement continuous security monitoring for all critical assets 2. Conduct monthly tabletop exercises for different attack scenarios 3. Establish direct communication channels with law enforcement cyber units 4. Deploy deception technology to detect lateral movement faster 5. Create automated incident response workflows for common scenarios Classification: CONFIDENTIAL Distribution: Incident Response Team, Executive Leadership Next Review: January 15, 2026
